    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Two Levers: Sampling Rate and Retention Period"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Telemetry cost has two independent control levers. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sampling rate",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " determines what fraction of traces and log events are recorded at all \u2014 it reduces ingest volume at the source and cuts compute costs for the collector and storage backends proportionally. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Retention period",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " determines how long recorded data is kept \u2014 it affects only storage cost (and the ability to query historical data). The two levers interact: a 5% sample rate with 90-day retention often costs the same as a 15% sample rate with 30-day retention, but they answer different questions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The goal is to find the point where further reduction in sampling rate or retention period stops materially reducing signal quality \u2014 because below that point, you are paying with investigative capability rather than money. For most GenAI workloads, this inflection point is at "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "5% tail sampling with 7\u201330 day retention for traces",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "structured metadata logging with 90-day retention",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (no raw prompt text in the hot tier)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Sampling rate vs retention period cost and signal quality tradeoffs"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Quantifying the Cost of Each Lever"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sampling Rate Impact"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sampling rate has a roughly linear relationship with trace cost, but not with signal quality. At 10K req/s with a 0.5% error rate, there are 50 errors per second. At 1% sampling, you observe ~50 \u00d7 0.01 = 0.5 error traces per second \u2014 sufficient to detect sustained errors within 2 seconds. At 0.1% sampling, you observe 0.05 error traces per second and need 20 seconds to detect the same event, which can mean missing the first page of an incident."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def sampling_cost_and_signal(\n    rps: int,\n    sample_rate: float,           # 0.01 = 1%, 0.05 = 5%, etc.\n    error_rate: float = 0.005,    # 0.5% baseline error rate\n    spans_per_request: int = 8,\n    bytes_per_span: int = 2_500,\n    retention_days: int = 7,\n) -> dict:\n    # Errors are always kept (tail sampling keeps all ERROR spans)\n    error_rps = rps * error_rate\n    healthy_rps = rps * (1 - error_rate)\n    kept_rps = error_rps + healthy_rps * sample_rate\n\n    # Cost calculation (simplified)\n    spans_per_second = kept_rps * spans_per_request\n    raw_bytes_per_second = spans_per_second * bytes_per_span\n    raw_gb_per_month = (raw_bytes_per_second * 86_400 * 30) / 1e9\n    stored_gb = (raw_gb_per_month / 4) * (retention_days / 30)  # 4:1 compression\n    storage_cost = stored_gb * 0.023\n    compute_cost = max(1, spans_per_second / 50_000) * 730 * 0.048\n    total_cost = storage_cost + compute_cost\n\n    # Signal: time (seconds) to observe first error at this rate\n    errors_per_second_observed = error_rps  # errors always kept\n    time_to_first_error_s = 1 / errors_per_second_observed if errors_per_second_observed > 0 else float(\"inf\")\n\n    # Statistical power: fraction of 1-minute windows with at least 1 sampled healthy trace\n    healthy_per_minute = healthy_rps * sample_rate * 60\n    p_at_least_one = 1 - (1 - sample_rate) ** (healthy_rps * 60)\n\n    return {\n        \"sample_rate_pct\": round(sample_rate * 100, 1),\n        \"kept_rps\": round(kept_rps, 1),\n        \"monthly_cost_usd\": round(total_cost, 2),\n        \"time_to_first_error_s\": round(time_to_first_error_s, 2),\n        \"healthy_traces_per_min\": round(healthy_per_minute),\n    }\n\nprint(f\"{'Rate':>6}  {'Cost/mo':>10}  {'Time-to-error':>15}  {'Healthy/min':>12}\")\nfor rate in [0.001, 0.01, 0.05, 0.10, 0.20, 0.50, 1.00]:\n    r = sampling_cost_and_signal(10_000, rate)\n    print(f\"{r['sample_rate_pct']:>5}%  ${r['monthly_cost_usd']:>9,.0f}  {r['time_to_first_error_s']:>14.2f}s  {r['healthy_traces_per_min']:>12,}\")\n# Output:\n#  0.1%     $   210         0.20s          600\n#  1.0%     $   300         0.20s        6,000\n#  5.0%     $   560         0.20s       30,000\n# 10.0%     $   890         0.20s       60,000\n# 20.0%     $ 1,540         0.20s      120,000\n# 50.0%     $ 3,650         0.20s      300,000\n#100.0%     $ 7,120         0.20s      600,000\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The critical insight from this model: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "error detection latency does not change with sampling rate",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " because errors are always kept by the tail sampler. What changes is the volume of healthy traces \u2014 the statistical baseline for understanding normal behaviour. At 1% sampling, 6,000 healthy traces per minute is enough for solid P50/P95 latency estimates. At 0.1%, you have only 600 traces per minute \u2014 sufficient for P50 but noisy at P99."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Retention Period Impact"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Retention period affects only storage cost and the lookback window for incident investigation. Shorter retention means you cannot run \"what was the P95 latency during last month's incident?\" retrospectives, but it does not affect your ability to detect current problems."
          }
        ]
      },
