      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For traces specifically, 7-day retention covers 95%+ of incident post-mortems (most incidents are investigated within 24\u201372 hours). Extending to 30 days covers the remaining cases where a subtle regression was noticed a week later. Beyond 30 days, trace retention buys you trend analysis that is better served by metrics (which are far cheaper to store long-term)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Decision Framework: Choosing the Right Point"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Apply this decision framework for each signal type independently. The questions differ because metrics, logs, and traces serve different investigative purposes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Traces: Decision Questions"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "What is your error rate? "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If < 1%, tail sampling already keeps all meaningful errors. Sampling rate only affects your healthy baseline volume \u2014 start at 5%."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "What is your P99 latency relative to median? "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If P99 is 5\u00d7 P50, a 5% sample captures enough latency outliers for statistical significance. If P99 is 50\u00d7 P50 (bimodal), consider raising to 10% to capture the outlier distribution better."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Do you have model evaluation traces? "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Keep 100% of eval traces unconditionally \u2014 they are low volume and high diagnostic value."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "What is the longest post-incident investigation window your team actually uses? "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Set retention to that + 20%. Most teams discover it is 7\u201314 days, not 90."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Logs: Decision Questions"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Are you logging prompt and response text? "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "This is the single largest cost driver. If you are, move to metadata-only logging (model, tokens, cost, finish_reason, latency) and store text only in a separate restricted tenant with 30-day retention. This typically cuts log volume by 60\u201380%."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "What log levels reach production? "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Debug logs should never reach the production Loki tenant. Set Vector/Fluentd to drop DEBUG and TRACE before ingest. This cuts volume by 30\u201350% for verbose applications."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "What is your log line size? "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "A log line with 10 well-chosen fields averages 400 bytes. A log line that includes nested objects or arrays can reach 5KB. Flatten log schemas and drop unused fields at the structlog layer."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Metrics: Decision Questions"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "How many active Prometheus series do you have per service? "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Run "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "count({job='your-service'}) by (__name__)",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " and sum. > 50,000 series per service is a cardinality problem. Identify the label with highest cardinality and hash or drop it."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Are you histogramming things that don't need percentiles? "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "A histogram creates 15+ series per metric (one per bucket). If you only need P50 and P99, consider using a summary instead. If you only need averages, use a counter + gauge."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "What is your scrape interval? "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "The default 15s scrape interval generates 4\u00d7 the data of 60s. For GenAI metrics that change slowly (daily cost, model quality scores), a 60s or even 5m scrape interval is appropriate."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Telemetry Budget Decision Tree"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "markdown"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Start here when evaluating whether to increase or decrease telemetry investment:\n\n1. Is your telemetry cost > 1% of LLM API spend?\n   NO \u2192 Current spend is proportionate. Optimise only if absolute $ is a concern.\n   YES \u2192 Continue.\n\n2. Is the overspend in logs, traces, or metrics?\n   LOGS \u2192 Step 3.\n   TRACES \u2192 Step 5.\n   METRICS \u2192 Step 7.\n\n3. Are you logging prompt/response text in the hot tier?\n   YES \u2192 Move to metadata-only logging. Expected saving: 60-80% of log cost.\n   NO \u2192 Step 4.\n\n4. Are DEBUG logs reaching Loki?\n   YES \u2192 Drop at Vector/Fluentd. Expected saving: 30-50%.\n   NO \u2192 Reduce retention from 90d \u2192 30d. Expected saving: 67%.\n\n5. Is your tail sampling rate > 10%?\n   YES \u2192 Reduce to 5%. Expected saving: 45-50% of trace cost.\n   NO \u2192 Step 6.\n\n6. Is trace retention > 14 days?\n   YES \u2192 Reduce to 7 days for healthy traces, 30 days for error traces only.\n          Expected saving: 50-75% of trace storage.\n   NO \u2192 Review span size. Are you setting large string attributes per span?\n        Strip them (they belong in logs, not spans).\n\n7. Do you have > 50K active series per service?\n   YES \u2192 Run cardinality audit. Likely a high-cardinality label (user_id, request_id).\n          Hash or drop it. Expected saving: 50-80% of metric cost.\n   NO \u2192 Check scrape interval. Raise to 60s if 15s. Expected saving: 75%.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Practical Cost Optimisation Recipes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Recipe 1: Log Volume Reduction (highest ROI)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# structlog configuration: drop fields that inflate log size\nimport structlog\n\ndef drop_large_fields(logger, method, event_dict):\n    \"\"\"Remove fields that inflate log size without adding query value.\"\"\"\n    # Never log prompt/response text in the operational tier\n    event_dict.pop(\"prompt_text\", None)\n    event_dict.pop(\"response_text\", None)\n    event_dict.pop(\"system_prompt\", None)\n\n    # Remove nested dicts \u2014 flatten at source instead\n    for key in list(event_dict):\n        if isinstance(event_dict[key], dict) and len(str(event_dict[key])) > 500:\n            event_dict[key] = f\"<truncated:{len(str(event_dict[key]))}b>\"\n\n    return event_dict\n\nstructlog.configure(processors=[\n    drop_large_fields,\n    structlog.processors.JSONRenderer(),\n])\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
