        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The two cost levers \u2014 sampling rate and retention period \u2014 have different relationships with signal quality. Sampling rate affects how many healthy traces you observe per minute (statistical baseline quality), while errors are always kept by tail sampling regardless of rate. A 5% sampling rate at 10K req/s gives 30,000 healthy traces per minute \u2014 more than enough for P95 latency estimates \u2014 while reducing trace cost by 90% compared to 100% sampling. Retention period affects only storage cost and lookback window: 7 days covers 95% of post-mortems; 30 days covers the rest; beyond 30 days, trend data is better served by metrics. The highest-ROI optimisations, in order, are: dropping prompt/response text from the operational log tier (60\u201380% log cost reduction), eliminating debug logs before Loki ingest (30\u201350%), reducing trace retention from 90 to 7\u201314 days (75% storage reduction), and auditing metric label cardinality for high-cardinality labels like "
